Allianz, Bayer, Deutsche Bank, RWE, VW: German Equity Preview

-- B y   J a n a   R a n d o w
-- 
2011-07-04T06:31:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-03/allianz-bayer-deutsche-bank-rwe-vw-german-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in  Germany . Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close.  The benchmark  DAX index (DAX)  increased 0.6 percent to 7,419.44.  Allianz SE (ALV)  :  Europe ’s largest insurer plans to roll
over 300 million euros ($436 million) of Greek  government bonds 
as part of a private-sector contribution to a second aid package
for the debt-strapped nation. The shares gained 1.1 percent to
97.43 euros.  Bayer AG (BAYN)  : Bayer’s CropScience unit agreed to a
$750 million settlement resolving claims with about 11,000 U.S.
farmers who said a strain of the company’s genetically modified
rice tainted crops and ruined their export value. The shares
increased 0.4 percent to 55.67 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI)  : Chief Executive Officer Dieter Zetsche
said the company would welcome more Chinese investors, Bild
reported. The shares dropped 0.6 percent to 51.59 euros.  Deutsche Bank AG (DBK)  : Chairman  Clemens Boersig  wants
to finish his search for a successor to Chief Executive Officer
 Josef Ackermann  by September, Financial Times Deutschland
reported, without saying where it got the information. The
shares jumped 2.6 percent to 41.81 euros.  Grenkeleasing AG (GLJ)  : The company that leases computer
equipment to small businesses said new business in the group,
including franchise partners, rose 25.6 percent to 409 million
euros ($594 million).  RWE AG (RWE)  : Germany’s second-largest utility is
considering a sale of its Npower unit in the U.K., according to
a person familiar with the matter.  Separately, RWE is seeking “fair compensation” for
damages caused by Germany’s plan to phase out nuclear energy,
Chief Executive Officer  Juergen Grossmann  told Frankfurter
Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung. The shares climbed 1.5 percent to
38.82 euros.  Volkswagen AG (VOW)  : The carmaker plans to publish a
statement around 9 a.m. July 4 on the final result of its tender
offer for  MAN SE (MAN)  . Volkswagen’s shares rose 0.9 percent
to 127.85 euros, MAN’s shares advanced 3.6 percent to 95.30
euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jana Randow in  Frankfurt  at 
 jrandow@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Craig Stirling at   cstirling1@bloomberg.net  